<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-827-172  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 827 172.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacUser  Dec 1989 v5 n12 p229(3)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>SCSI solutions. (using and understandingsmall-computer-system-interface devices) (Power Tools) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Coale, Kristi.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Small-computer-system-interface (SCSI) devices add functionalityto the Macintosh, but they also make the way the machine readssignals more complicated.andP;  Confusion centers around addressing andtermination.andP;  A single daisy chain is used to connect SCSIdevices, but the total length should not exceed 18 feet.andP;  Eachdevice must have a unique numeric address between 0 and 7; theMacintosh is a SCSI device with address 7, and an Apple-installedinternal hard disk in an SE or II has a default SCSI address of 0.andO;How to pick appropriate SCSI address is discussed.andP;  A SCSIterminator is a resistor that reduces signal echoing along a chainof devices, and while any SCSI device can be terminated, Applerecommends that only the first and last be terminated.andP;  Theinternal terminators in many SCSI devices confuse the issueconsiderably; how to determine whether a device has an internalterminator is discussed, and a SCSI diagnostic checklist isprovided.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (usage).andO;Topic:     Disk DrivesSystem DesignTutorialSmall Computer Systems InterfaceMicrocomputers.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Hard disks with and without internal SCSI terminators. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>SCSI SolutionsandM;Small-computer-system-interface (SCSIe devices bring more functionality tothe Mac, but they also introduce complications in the way the Mac readssignals--even from an internal hard-disk drive.andP;  Some conflicts are seriousenough to damage your data or Mac, but most are common and easy to fix.andP;  Thetwo most common points of SCSI confusion are addressing and termination.andP;  Ifyou follow the guidelines below and still have problems, check the tips inthe SCSI Diagnostic Checklist.andO;</TEXT></DOC>